Note that in each trial there is a variable amount of money in the combined earning, so that two equal split_self variables do not represent the same "fairness".

trial_role = the role of the participant [1 = responder, 2 = proposer]
token_opp = number of tokens found by the opponent
token_self = number of tokens found by the participant
combined_earning = amount of money earned in total (note that each token found is £3)
split_opp = the proposed share of the opponent (in £)
split_self = the proposed share for the participant (in £)
splitperc_opp = same but in %

accept = whether the participant responded accept (1) or reject (0)

Step-by-step reasoning:
1. Key psychological mechanisms:
 • Fairness concerns: Responders feel a disutility when the offer is lower than what they expect as fair.
 • Learning from experience: Instead of assuming a fixed “fair” share (i.e. a 50/50 split), the responder updates an internal fairness norm (a learned expectation) based on previous offers.
 • Inequality aversion: The disutility is proportional to the shortfall from the learned fairness norm.

2. Interaction of mechanisms:
 • On each trial the responder compares the actual monetary split for themselves (split_self) to the fairness norm computed as the product of the current fairness estimate and the combined earnings.
 • If the offer falls short of this norm, a penalty is incurred, weighted by a sensitivity parameter (‘alpha’).
 • After experiencing the offer, the responder updates their fairness expectation using a delta rule with a learning rate.

3. Mathematical form:
 • Let f_t be the learned fairness norm (expressed as a fraction) at trial t.
 • The utility of accepting an offer on trial t is:
  U_accept(t) = split_self(t) – alpha · max[(f_t · combined_earning(t) – split_self(t)), 0]
 • The fairness norm is updated following:
  f_(t+1) = f_t + learning_rate · (o(t) – f_t)
  where o(t) is the observed fairness proportion derived from the received offer (i.e. splitperc_self/100).

4. Learnable parameters and calibration:
 • alpha: captures the sensitivity to a shortfall in fairness; its bounds can be set generously (e.g., [0,10]).
 • learning_rate: regulates how quickly the fairness norm is updated; bounded between 0 and 1.

5. Mapping to observable behavior:
 • The observable offer variables split_self, combined_earning and splitperc_self are taken from the dataset.
 • The utility computed predicts responder acceptance based on the trade-off between the material payoff (split_self) and the fairness shortfall penalty.

Step-by-step reasoning:
1. Key psychological mechanisms:
 • Fairness concerns: Responders feel a disutility when the offer is lower than what they expect as fair.
 • Learning from experience: Instead of assuming a fixed “fair” share (i.e. a 50/50 split), the responder updates an internal fairness norm (a learned expectation) based on previous offers.
 • Inequality aversion: The disutility is proportional to the shortfall from the learned fairness norm.

2. Interaction of mechanisms:
 • On each trial the responder compares the actual monetary split for themselves (split_self) to the fairness norm computed as the product of the current fairness estimate and the combined earnings.
 • If the offer falls short of this norm, a penalty is incurred, weighted by a sensitivity parameter (‘alpha’).
 • After experiencing the offer, the responder updates their fairness expectation using a delta rule with a learning rate.

3. Mathematical form:
 • Let f_t be the learned fairness norm (expressed as a fraction) at trial t.
 • The utility of accepting an offer on trial t is:
  U_accept(t) = split_self(t) – alpha · max[(f_t · combined_earning(t) – split_self(t)), 0]
 • The fairness norm is updated following:
  f_(t+1) = f_t + learning_rate · (o(t) – f_t)
  where o(t) is the observed fairness proportion derived from the received offer (i.e. splitperc_self/100).

4. Learnable parameters and calibration:
 • alpha: captures the sensitivity to a shortfall in fairness; its bounds can be set generously (e.g., [0,10]).
 • learning_rate: regulates how quickly the fairness norm is updated; bounded between 0 and 1.

5. Mapping to observable behavior:
 • The observable offer variables split_self, combined_earning and splitperc_self are taken from the dataset.
 • The utility computed predicts responder acceptance based on the trade-off between the material payoff (split_self) and the fairness shortfall penalty.
